# 🏷 Creating Spring Beans

## 1️⃣ Using @Component

```java id="sb3"
import org.springframework.stereotype.Component;

@Component
public class Student {

}
```

Spring automatically detects and creates the Bean.

---

## 2️⃣ Using @Service

Used for business logic.

```java id="sb4"
@Service
public class StudentService {

}
```

---

## 3️⃣ Using @Repository

Used for database operations.

```java id="sb5"
@Repository
public class StudentRepository {

}
```

---

## 4️⃣ Using @Controller

Used in Spring MVC.

```java id="sb6"
@Controller
public class HomeController {

}
```

---

## 5️⃣ Using @RestController

Used for REST APIs.

```java id="sb7"
@RestController
public class StudentController {

}
```

---

## 6️⃣ Using @Bean Annotation

Beans can also be created manually.

```java id="sb8"
@Configuration
public class AppConfig {

    @Bean
    public Student student() {
        return new Student();
    }

}
```

